narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Continuing knowledge of Calc I, quantitative reasoning
This course was very challenging, and thus it taught me how to think outside of the box and how to master difficult concepts.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The course is well organized and it is always clear on canvas what assignments are due and when. The schedule has a very consistent structure which is helpful when planning your week. However, my section fell behind halfway through the semester and we often had to complete preclass assignments based on what we were supposed to have learned during the previous class, except my section had not yet covered. This forced me to learn a lot of the topics on my own.
Course is fine for an intro course. The general setup of explores and psets was generally helpful.
I found this course quite difficult under the lecture environment, and I sometimes learned more through self-study. Perhaps more engagement would be helpful.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I wouldn't take it unless it is a prerequisite for another course that you want to take or you really enjoy math.

I've taken Calc 2 in high school and that was the only reason I succeeded in this course. I think it would be very hard to learn new material in this course unless you get the Course Admin as your professor. If you haven't taken calc 2 before, do not take this class with a grad student.

Yes, if you need to take it. As far as math classes go, it is very well structured and there is a lot of support from peer tutors and review sessions to help study. The p-sets were manageable, but for my schedule, the Wednesday deadlines were a bit difficult. I also would prefer if the review sessions all followed the format of the first one, which was basically a summary of what we needed to know.

Not unless it is required. Many of the instructors are hard to follow, and we're so flooded with information that it's hard to organize. I found that I wouldn't understand how things connect and what we need to know until the review sessions before exams, weeks after learning the actual material .
I would not unless the student has a profound interest in math, as I found it to be quite difficult.
It's not terrible, but it's not exactly engaging either.
